{{! ============================== OVERVIEW ============================== }}
<section id="overview">
<h2>Overview</h2>

<p>Unified Grader replaces Moodle's per-activity grading screens with a single
two-panel interface: <strong>submission preview on the left</strong>,
<strong>marking on the right</strong>. The same interface grades assignments,
forum discussions, quizzes, and BigBlueButton sessions — switching activity
type just swaps the adapter behind the scenes.</p>

<p>Use it whenever a Moodle activity has <em>something to look at and
something to mark</em>. The plugin doesn't introduce its own grade store;
grades land in the standard gradebook and per-activity grading tables, the
same place they would if you graded through Moodle's native UI.</p>

<div class="local-unifiedgrader-help-screenshot">
    <i class="fa fa-image" aria-hidden="true"></i>
    <span>Screenshot: full grading interface (assignment), labelled to show the
    student navigator (top right), preview pane (left), marking panel (right),
    and toolbar pills.</span>
</div>

<h3>Key benefits</h3>
<ul>
    <li><strong>One UI for every gradable activity.</strong> Less context-switch when grading mixed-type courseware.</li>
    <li><strong>PDF annotation</strong> with comments, stamps, freehand drawing, and text highlight / strikethrough — flattened into a downloadable annotated PDF for the student.</li>
    <li><strong>Rich feedback editor</strong> (TinyMCE) including audio/video recording.</li>
    <li><strong>Comment library</strong> with tags, sharing across markers, universal &amp; system-default comments, and autocomplete inside marking-guide remarks.</li>
    <li><strong>Academic-integrity referral</strong> — flag a submission for review (pausing the turnaround clock) and open your institution's report form in one click.</li>
    <li><strong>Auto-save</strong> with offline IndexedDB cache and retry queue — your work isn't lost on a flaky connection.</li>
    <li><strong>Pluggable adapter</strong> design — additional activity types can be wired in without touching the UI.</li>
</ul>
</section>

{{! ============================ QUICK START ============================ }}
<section id="quickstart">
<h2>Quick start (teachers)</h2>

<ol>
    <li><strong>Open the grader.</strong> From a supported activity's view page, click <em>Unified Grader</em> in the secondary navigation tab bar (just after <em>Edit settings</em>), or click the <em>Grade</em> / <em>Grade users</em> button — the plugin replaces the native action with a redirect to the grader.</li>
    <li><strong>Pick a student.</strong> Use the prev/next arrows in the top-right toolbar, the counter (<em>3 / 24</em>), or open the navigator (<i class="fa fa-bars" aria-hidden="true"></i>) to filter/search/sort.</li>
    <li><strong>Review the submission</strong> in the left pane — PDFs render with annotation tools; forum posts, quiz attempts, and BBB recordings render in their natural form.</li>
    <li><strong>Mark on the right</strong> — enter a grade, write feedback, attach files, add private notes. Save explicitly with <em>Save feedback</em> or rely on auto-save when you focus out of the form.</li>
    <li><strong>Post grades</strong> when you're ready: the toggle in the toolbar reveals/hides the gradebook column for students. Schedule a future post date if your workflow allows.</li>
</ol>

<div class="alert alert-info">
    <strong>Help is contextual.</strong> The <i class="fa fa-question-circle" aria-hidden="true"></i> icon
    deep-links to the section of this page matching the activity type you're grading.
</div>
</section>

